[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering resource issues in testing**\n\nI'm thinking about how JaCoCo instrumented effective classes work. If the resource comes from a JAR, that's still okay as the agent should track dynamic aspects. I want to prefer using the test's context class loader since Gradle likely includes the instrumented directory on the classpath. However, if resources are unavailable, that could lead to an AssertionError, which isn't ideal for native images. I really need to find a way to handle these cases to ensure our tests run smoothly.\n\n**Evaluating resource assertions in native images**\n\nI'm considering if I can assert that a resource exists on the JVM. In native images, it might exist, but it's uncertain. Native images might not necessarily include class resources, and existing metadata may or may not contain them. I think I should avoid this path under native conditions, but I can't use guards effectively. It might be wise to catch an IllegalStateException, but missing resources aren't classified as dynamic loading issues. Ultimately, if native images don't include class resources, the test fails.\n\n**Evaluating class loading**\n\nI'm looking into how Class.forName returns Class. It seems this load doesn't expose methods directly, and I don't need to invoke typeIndex in isolation — static initialization is sufficient. That's good! I think I might not need direct reflection at all. Just using Class.forName could work. My task involves dynamic access, which is acceptable, so I'll consider making some edits to streamline this.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_03e522aa32a0016e0169fa05349a10819ea2eb86504ea926e5\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-gVCrUAJjola5QQYs7ck3_MYmWMkWLuwSpvAeqZp9NelnjGaYpGeQesf9DYnLpLH-wauoEAflngi6PR16EkMVbma1ohCI1d5qZ8Q8f-CbxmMRFEuOIBmpRbl4vj4JCuyKM-NBvrFWE4tGB6Zq71Y3M_T5DB98B8IhUWqK8SYHBXvfukLCJSTA-0KE993ILrXPc_iQ